Sep 29 2008 	Shocking	We have just returned from an evenings stay at the Hempel Hotel, which is described on your web site as a 5 Star Luxury boutique hotel. Based on our stay I believe that this description is far from correct, based on the level of service and the standard of our room provided by the hotel.Service On arrival on Friday 26th September we checked in to The Hempel, and as requested I handed over my debit card to guarantee our room. Reception then proceeded in charging the cost of our room plus a considerable amount to deposit against any extras straight away onto my card without informing me of this, this totalling £350. This amount was not discussed with myself and had it been discussed I would have explained that I did not require any extras therefore did not want to pay any extras, due to other arrangements had been made by ourselves for the rest of our stay in London. Upon checking out of the Hempel 27th Sept, I was issued a refund of £112.67. You must agree that this shows that the amount I had taken from my Card was considerably above the cost of the room. You should be made aware that when a payment is taken with switch it is debited instantly, however the refund will not be credited back into my account until 30th Sept, 3 days after being issued. Another issue I would like to bring to your attention is that your staff failed to show any interest in us as guests. We were not informed of any of the hotels facilities despite telling them we had not stayed there before, we were not made to feel very welcome at all.HotelOn the hotels website you are very keen to mention the luxury of all of the rooms, however I feel that the rooms were very much based on look rather than the finish. The room was very basic with what seemed like painted mdf doors on the wardrobes and cupboards. The bathroom was also poorly finished with taps that looked as though they hadn’t been wiped for a week rather than that day. Also the bath tap was facing upwards and when in use a stream of water ran out of the base of the tap and down the wall, this is not what I would consider as luxury. Within the seated area there were two doors opening onto a small balcony, these didn’t lock. There was also an electrical item that had failed a PAT test and in a luxury hotel I would expect small details to have been fixed at the time of failure.On entry to the room a large bed greets you, which upon getting into at night we were disappointed to find that this was in fact two beds pushed together, which always leads to one person sleeping in the gap all night. Considering I had booked a double room this appeared to be a twin room made to look like a double once again the look of the room was put before the comfort of the guest as one large bed would have been more comfortable and wouldn’t have detracted from the impact of the room. My disappointment was only heightened when I returned home to remember that I had made a conscious decision to book a Deluxe room. I can only begin to imagine what a Superior room would have been like. I only wish that the look of a bright and airy luxurious hotel too which was shown on the website had been carried over to what we felt was a dark and dingy overrated hotel and glad that I didn’t pay for the guaranteed garden view as during our stay we would have had a lovely view of a marquee. This also meant we were unable to enjoy the Zen garden as advertised on you website.During a recent stay in a luxury hotel, we stayed in a Malmaison, which left the Hempel looking more like a 3 star hotel, when in my opinion it should be the other way round, based that it is from a chain of hotels, I only wish that this had been the case based on a difference of £100 per night. Overall our stay at the Hempel was disappointing and we will not be recommending this hotel. However our feelings towards your hotel do not reflect the rest of the service we received from other establishments where we were made to feel very welcome. Our stay 