Apr 26 2008 	Mutton Dressed As Lamb	I feel a bit naïve for not having read the reviews here prior to booking, but I had the perception of the Hempel being the kind of class act you wouldn’t need to scrutinise before reserving a room. That was one mistake.My other mistake was to request a late check out. My partner and I were celebrating a special occasion and we did not want to be in a rush to check out on the Sunday morning. In my experience, some hotels will willingly assist you in this, if it is at all possible. Some will charge and some will not. I will not go into minute detail, but it was an arduous process to get the reservations desk to record merely even the request next to my room reservation. My request was allowed only after being kept waiting for 30 minutes to check in to our room, and after this I assumed that everything would be fine. But unfortunately, it wasn’t.We arrived in good time for check in – however were kept waiting in the bar until our room was ready for some 40 minutes or more. We kept having to check with the staff on reception as to whether our room was ready for us. Whilst waiting around for our room, my partner commented on how the hotel looked quite dated for an ultra modern hotel with a minimalist look and feel. Earlier before the check in saga, as we had driven to the hotel, upon arrival we asked for directions to park our car. We drove around the block to find a space which was suitable. Note to the Hempel: negotiate parking spaces with your locality, as your guests may have had to endure a long drive in the first place to the hotel – not everyone wants to spend another 40 mins or so, looking for parking!!!Our hotel room was OK – nothing special. We expected more from a Deluxe bedroom. Be aware that the walls at the Hempel are very thin. You can hear every knock on the floor and every door shutting. Not to mention the lift ‘ping’ every time the lift stops on your floor!On the Sunday afternoon at 1.30pm, after returning from a stroll, and upon ordering some tea from room service we received a call from the reception telling us that we should vacate our room because it had been noted that we had not yet left and we were reminded that we should have checked out at 12pm because all the rooms were booked. I explained to the man on the front desk that he must have his facts wrong as our late check had been agreed and confirmed with the man who had checked us in, so I told him to check his facts and call me back. He did this and called back, but instead of confirming that they had made an error he reaffirmed his request to have us vacate as soon as possible. Again, I told him to check his information and that I was definitely not lying to him even though he was not trusting what I was saying to him. Since both my partner and I were now stressed out, I went down to the reception to discuss it in person to sort out the whole matter face to face. It was only at this stage that they acknowledged there had been a mistake. They said they were sorry, but not in any meaningful way after the stress they had caused. But to add to this, my partner had had a conversation with the maid who was servicing our floor while I was downstairs sorting out our late check out at reception. The maid clearly knew what time we were to check out, and yet the front desk didn’t have a clue! And when our tea arrived shortly after this episode, without prompting, the man from room service talked about how quiet it often is on a Sunday afternoon and that they had several rooms that were vacant at that time on this day since most people checked in on the Monday. So clearly I was lied to by the man on reception who had created the impression that we were somehow preventing someone else from coming in our room by checking out later - bloody cheek!I think this kind of behaviour is totally unacceptable from an establishment which is positioning itself in the marketplace as a calming and revitalising refuge. Is the idea that you should rest before they stress you out before leaving? If this is the case then job well done!A positive point to note about the hotel, is that the room service staff and maids are attentive and friendly. On every occasion we were greeted with a friendly smile, and their helpfulness made our stay more bearable.As a closing note, the décor of the rooms may have been new and different once (they now look a little dated and cheap), but unfortunately there are now about 100 other hotels out there with similar - if not far better - clean modern interior design, the main difference overall is that they probably treat their clientele far better than the Hempel.My partner and I shall definitely not be returning to the Hempel and would recommend others considering this establishment to think again and book elsewhere!Trouble and Mischief	
