Mar 3 2006	Not a 5* Hotel	We stayed at the Hempel for 3 nights in a superior bedroom. We felt comfortable in the Hotel but for the price i have some complaints:1. The shower/tub is standing exactly in front of a window. You cannot see through 3/4 of the glas but cannot conceal the top quater. At the other side of the courtyard is a higher building so people can watch you showering - females, watch out, they can see your upper body!2. The fittings and the interior in the bathroom is 3* at most.3. Some of the (many)lights in the room and in the aisle did not work.4. The air-condition was too loud and you could not regulate the temperature but the presetting was ok most of the time.4. The multi-media equipment is poor for a 5* hotel but it is not a 5*-hotel so....But as we spend most of our time in town and not in the room, it was not a major problem - and yes, there is a CD-player but no CD's.I liked the hall, the restaurant/ breakfast room, the colores, the space in the room and the overall design.Some of the staff seemed semi-skilled but was helpful.The Hotel is worth maybe 150 to 180€ per night and room, not more.But anyway, we enjoyed the stay and London very much but because of the overall cost/performance ratio we will not come again.	
Jan 23 2006 	OK but not fantastic	We stayed at the Hempel on a Saturday night having booked a studio appartment on a discounted offer. On arrival as there were no studio apartments available we were upgraded to a one bedroom apartment. For the price we were paying this was great but if we had been paying full price we would have been very disappointed. The first impression was great but small things such as the mould around the bath, the rusty shower rail and the standard of facilities in the kitchen area were very poor. Depite a 2pm check in time our room was not ready until nearly 3pm. Do not order a sandwich, they are a rip off at £10 for tinned tuna and cheap packet bread. We didn't try the restaurant so can't comment. We are going back to stay in a deluxe room in February so I look forward to comparing the experience!	
Dec 24 2005	Disappointed	On arrival at the Hempel, the reception area was extremely impressive, with it's sunken seating areas and candle glowing, white walled minimalistic environment. Our room was a suite / appartment located directly across the road (with kitchen). Inside it was exceptionally clean, with nice white robes and a large bed with crisp white sheets. So why where we disappointed. Because we booked a 5 star experience and received a 3 star clean tidy hotel. A tiny bathroom, with over the bath shower (great for 3 star but not 5 star luxury). Music was offered from a £30 old fashioned music centre i kid you not (music moguls stay here???), the TV a basic small cheap wall mounted plasma, two wicker chairs and a table - that was it. The famous bar downstairs: flat, no atmosphere, basic and boring. The barman was however super friendly (a bass guitarist) - thanks. We decided not to eat there in I-Thai, so can't comment.	
Dec 15 2005	Dissapointing	Very impressive welcome area and lounges gave way to dissapointment with the room and particularly the bathroom. The sink did not drain and the shower was useless. The evening meal was poor and overpriced with long delays between courses and there was a concentration on presentation of the dish rather than giving value for money and quality of taste.	
Nov 5 2005	the Hempel - promises more than delivers	Decided to take a last minute one night break and booked a room via a lastminute site for £200 per night.First impresions were excellent, the reception area has a great wow factor and spotlessly clean. There were lots of staff milling around....(the hotel is boasting a 3 staff to each guest ratio)...we just wer'nt sure what they were all doing including the new owner and general manager who all avoided eye contact or greetings.On entering our bedroom the first impression was good, but then we realised some of the designer lights were not working and there was heavy dust around the wardrobes and the struts of the 4 poster. The bathroom had a very heavy door with 2 marble steps down into the room, the bottom one wasn't as wide as the top one - these are a bit tricky to negotiate at night, especially without contact lenses!For a designer hotel the bath was tiny and poorly designed - you have to climb into the bath to close the bath plug. I was also dissapointed the tub wasn't large enough for two as there was plenty of room for a wider bath in the room. The water pressure however, was great so showering was a real joy.On our way down to dinner in their iThai restaurant we reported the broken lights, a chipped beer glass in the minibar and not being able to get the turner to play music... but no effort was made to replace the bulbs, or glass. Why have 3 staff to every guest if simple things like bulb replacement doesn't happen?. The tuner only works if you have CDs with you....so remember to take your own!!!Cocktails in the bar before dinner were great, unusual blends and very tasty, though at nearly £10 each we did expect a few nibbles to accompany them. A non smoking section would have been better rather than having to take our drinks to the opposite end of the lobby to another seating area where no one else was to avoid the smoke.Dinner in the restauant was dissapointing, enviroment was stunning, lit by tea lights, not very busy and plenty of room between tables. However, my request for rare beef was ignored (it came well done)- when I asked for the meal to be recooked they left my partners behind so he had finished his before I even started mine. The Restaurant Manager although present (again along with the new owner) made no effort to acknowledge the mistake and our waiter apologised by laughing at his mistake. When the bill arrived no acknowledgment was made of the mistake and they even added a service charge!! We asked for the restaurant Manager, who by that time had left, but the waiter did take the main course and the service off the bill. On check out, all the above was again mentioned to reception, who merely said she would tell her manager! All in all, the place looks great, has the wow factor but needs to get it's service level sorted. With so many modern contemporary hotels in London...I think we'll try a smaller establishment where service is at the top of their list....and give the Hemple a miss next time!	
Oct 28 2005 	Form over function	In September 05 I spent 4 days at the Hemple. The interior design is not user-friendly, more for show than comfort and utility, with the exception of the lobby and bar, which are lovely and functional and set a very modern tone accented with charming, warm crackling fires. The staff is very polite, young and friendly. The bowl of fruit was a nice touch, but replacing used dishes would have been appreciated.The room was at the end of a poorly lit hallway (style and light bulbs burned out both contributing factors), overlooking a modest garden. It was cold and boxy, totally white on white. I was told by staff how lucky I was to get this room, but after only a few hours sleep I was awakened by constant furniture moving above me. (There are no rugs on the floors.) Later that evening I inquired about the morning disturbance and was advised there was a conference room situated directly above my bedroom! A scheduled conference &quot;set up&quot; had started very early, followed by the conference of seemingly never ending, moving chairs. The staff then volunteered that no further conferences were booked before my date of departure. (I thought this must be the lucky part!)It was a task and a half to figure out the room lighting, particularly in the bathroom where dim was the style night and day, if the window shade was closed for privacy. For women it is near impossible to apply makeup and I assume men would have challenges shaving safely at the poorly lit mirror. There were no washclothes the first two days, hair on the floor from the previous guest, and the medicine cabinet had a broken door with some glass broken in the corner. In both the bath and bedroom, the minimalist darkening shades meant having light (without privacy) in the day or no light from outside. As for the tub, one could not bathe or shower easily without flooding the floor.The second day, room keys would not work for some rooms. After finally reentering my room, two lively fellows checked in next door unaware that the hotel's lack of accoustical design would enhance the sounds of partying all night. The metal double doors between our rooms did not block sound well. As a result, while the beds are very, very comfortable, there was little or no rest to be had. In spite of mentioning my disappointment politely to the front desk, there was never an offer of a discount or a room change. Rather, I was told it was unfortunate...it was one of the best rooms... the problems were troubling to hear...I was lucky to get that room...they were surprised. I choose not to be so lucky in the future by crossing this overpriced and uncomfortable hotel off my list. While the structure may be well suited for magazine spreads about highly stylized rooms, modernizing and finding alternative uses for old mansions, and the like, The Hemple's guest rooms as built and decorated are not very user-friendly and are definitely not worth the price. These are things the consistently kind and charming staff cannot fix.	
